svt_8b10b_data A utility class that encapsulates an individual unit of transfer in an 8b/10b encoding protocol. The object can be initialized with either eight bit data or ten bit data. Methods are present on the object to encode eight bit data into its ten bit representation, or decode ten bit data into its eight bit representation. The current running disparity must be provided to encode or decode the data properly, and the updated running disparity value is returned from these functions via a ref argument.

svt_i2c_master_monitor_def_toggle_cov_callback State coverage is a signal level coverage. State coverage applies to signals that are a minimum of two bits wide. In most cases, the states (also commonly referred to as coverage bins) can be easily identified as all possible combinations of the signal. This Coverage Callback consists having covergroup definition and declaration. This class' constructor gets the port configuration class handle and creating covergroups based on respective signal_enable set from port configuartion class for optional protocol signals.
svt_i2c_master_monitor_def_toggle_cov_data_callbacks This callback class defines default data and event information that are used to implement the coverage groups. The naming convention uses "def_cov_data" in the class names for easy identification of these classes. This class also includes implementations of the coverage methods that respond to the coverage requests by setting the coverage data and triggering the coverage events. This implementation does not include any coverage groups. The def_cov_data callbacks classes are extended from port monitor callback class.

svt_i2c_slave This class is UVM Driver that implements an I2C slave component. The events available at the slave driver are as follows : EVENT_START_DETECTED : signals START detection by slave
EVENT_STOP_DETECTED : signals STOP detection by slave
EVENT_ACK_RECEIVED : signals ACK received by slave
EVENT_NACK_RECEIVED : signals NACK received by slave
EVENT_ACK_GENERATED : signals ACK generated from slave
EVENT_NACK_GENERATED : signals NACK generated from slave
EVENT_SECOND_BYTE_GEN_CALL_ACK_GENERATED : signals ACK for second byte of general call by slave
svt_i2c_slave_addr_bit_stretching_sequence This sequence configure Slave for stretching the clock after each bit of Address byte, by making SCL line LOW with User define clk_stretch_time_addr_byte, which shows time for which the SCL line goes LOW.
svt_i2c_slave_agent I2C Slave Agent
svt_i2c_slave_byte_stretching_sequence This sequence configure Slave for stretching the clock after each byte, by making SCL line LOW with User define clk_stretch_time_after_byte, which shows time for which the SCL line goes LOW.
svt_i2c_slave_callback Description-Unavailable
svt_i2c_slave_data_bit_stretching_sequence This sequence configure Slave for stretching the clock after each bit of data byte, by making SCL line LOW with User define clk_stretch_time_data_byte, which shows time for which the SCL line goes LOW.
svt_i2c_slave_monitor This class is Monitor Receiver for I2C Slave The events available at the slave monitor are as follows : EVENT_START_CONDITION: signals START condition from master
EVENT_STOP_CONDITION : signals STOP condition from master
EVENT_ACK_RECEIVED : signals receiving ACK on bus
EVENT_NACK_RECEIVED : signals receiving NACK on bus
EVENT_START_BYTE : signals START BYTE from master
EVENT_GEN_CALL : signals GENERAL CALL command from master
EVENT_SLAVE_ADD_7_B : signals 7-bit slave address from master
EVENT_SLAVE_ADD_10_B : signals 10-bit slave address from master
EVENT_GET_PACKET : signals receiving a data byte on bus
EVENT_REPEATED_START_CONDITION : signals REPEATED START condition

svt_i2c_slave_monitor_def_cov_data_callbacks The coverage data callback class defines default data and event information that are used to implement the coverage groups. The coverage data callback class is extended from callback class svt_i2c_slave_monitor_callback . This class itself does not contain any cover groups.
svt_i2c_slave_monitor_def_toggle_cov_callback State coverage is a signal level coverage. State coverage applies to signals that are a minimum of two bits wide. In most cases, the states (also commonly referred to as coverage bins) can be easily identified as all possible combinations of the signal. This Coverage Callback consists having covergroup definition and declaration. This class' constructor gets the port configuration class handle and creating covergroups based on respective signal_enable set from port configuartion class for optional protocol signals.
svt_i2c_slave_monitor_def_toggle_cov_data_callbacks This callback class defines default data and event information that are used to implement the coverage groups. The naming convention uses "def_cov_data" in the class names for easy identification of these classes. This class also includes implementations of the coverage methods that respond to the coverage requests by setting the coverage data and triggering the coverage events. This implementation does not include any coverage groups. The def_cov_data callbacks classes are extended from port monitor callback class.

svt_pattern Simple data object for describing patterns as name/value pairs along with match characteristics. In addition to the name/value information this includes match_min and match_max Used to define whether the match should repeat Typical matches: If match_min == 1 and match_max == 1 then the match must occur once and only once If match_min == 0 and match == n for some positive n then the match is expected to occur for "up to n" contiguous instances. positive_match (pattern_data) Stored with each name/value pair this indicates whether the individual name/value pair defines a match or mismatch request. positive_match (pattern) Stored with the pattern, indicating whether the overall pattern defines a match or mismatch request. gap_pattern Patterns can sometimes need to describe non-contiguous sequences. In these situations the non-contiguous nature of the match must be described by defining the gaps between the desired match elements. Each gap is itself stored as a pattern, but with the gap_pattern flag set. When set to true the pattern is used to do the match, but is not stored in the match results.
